{"parentUuid":"c6c30d34-fefb-43ad-9ce6-83ba82e7a50b","isSidechain":true,"userType":"external","cwd":"/home/ryan/formal-conjectures","sessionId":"15cb6920-dd91-4ef6-b199-875c11a65cc6","version":"2.1.71","gitBranch":"ai-erdos-7","agentId":"a7eed448bad883048","slug":"shimmering-snacking-willow","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01W8egfNqBChyfGEqTBuK3To","type":"tool_result","content":"# Erdős Problem #1147\n\n**Problem Number:** 1147\n\n**Status:** DISPROVED (solved in the negative)\n\n**Problem Statement:**\nLet α>0 be an irrational number. Is the set A={n≥1: ‖αn²‖ < 1/log n}, where ‖·‖ denotes the distance to the nearest integer, an additive basis of order 2?\n\n**Citation:** [Va99,1.21]\n\n**Tags:** irrational, additive basis\n\n**Resolution:**\nThe problem was disproved by Konieczny [Ko16b]. The statement is false both for almost every α>0 and specifically for α=√2.\n\n**General Result:**\nFor any ε(n)→0, the set A={n≥1: ‖αn²‖ < ε(n)} is not an additive basis of order 2 for almost every α>0.\n\n**Additional Information:**\n- LaTeX source available\n- Last edited: 27 January 2026\n- Comments: 2 comments on this problem\n- Formalised statement: No\n- Additional thanks to: Quanyu Tang\n- Navigation: Previous problem (#1146), Next problem (#1148)"}]},"uuid":"bce4228f-78b9-4d0c-8dc2-50ff782f6177","timestamp":"2026-03-11T14:36:29.800Z","sourceToolAssistantUUID":"c6c30d34-fefb-43ad-9ce6-83ba82e7a50b"}
{"parentUuid":"bce4228f-78b9-4d0c-8dc2-50ff782f6177","isSidechain":true,"userType":"external","cwd":"/home/ryan/formal-conjectures","sessionId":"15cb6920-dd91-4ef6-b199-875c11a65cc6","version":"2.1.71","gitBranch":"ai-erdos-7","agentId":"a7eed448bad883048","slug":"shimmering-snacking-willow","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_01CRXFTtwpPcYTuzSsUzsjC9","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Here is the full content from Erdos Problem #1147:\n\n- **Problem Number:** 1147\n- **Status:** DISPROVED (solved in the negative)\n- **Problem Statement:** Let alpha > 0 be an irrational number. Is the set A = {n >= 1 : ||alpha * n^2|| < 1/log n}, where ||.|| denotes the distance to the nearest integer, an additive basis of order 2?\n- **Citation:** [Va99, 1.21]\n- **Tags:** irrational, additive basis\n- **Resolution:** The problem was disproved by Konieczny [Ko16b]. The statement is false both for almost every alpha > 0 and specifically for alpha = sqrt(2).\n- **General Result:** For any epsilon(n) -> 0, the set A = {n >= 1 : ||alpha * n^2|| < epsilon(n)} is not an additive basis of order 2 for almost every alpha > 0.\n- **Additional metadata:**\n  - LaTeX source available\n  - Last edited: 27 January 2026\n  - Comments: 2 comments on this problem\n  - Formalised statement: No\n  - Additional thanks to: Quanyu Tang\n  - Navigation: Previous problem (#1146), Next problem (#1148)"}],"stop_reason":"end_turn","stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":433,"cache_read_input_tokens":17284,"output_tokens":313,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":433},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"}},"requestId":"req_011CYwThxCHVckm9xjbTPott","type":"assistant","uuid":"1b266ddb-b843-481c-aa97-506227f5b435","timestamp":"2026-03-11T14:36:35.601Z"}
